## Use Case: KSPM Network Policy Compliance

### Step 1 — Get Latest KSPM Scan ID (mandatory first step)

```dql
fetch security.events, from:-1d
| filter dt.system.bucket == "default_securityevents_builtin"
| filter event.type == "COMPLIANCE_FINDING"
| filter k8s.cluster.name == "${CLUSTER_NAME}"
| summarize latest = max(timestamp), by:{scan.id}
| sort latest desc
| limit 1
```

Save the `scan.id` value. Use it in all subsequent KSPM queries.

### Step 2 — Query Network Policy Findings (latest scan only)

Replace `<SCAN_ID>` with the value from Step 1.

```dql
fetch security.events, from:-1d
| filter dt.system.bucket == "default_securityevents_builtin"
| filter event.type == "COMPLIANCE_FINDING"
| filter scan.id == "<SCAN_ID>"
| filter contains(compliance.result.object.name, "unguard")
| filter contains(lower(compliance.rule.title), "network")
| summarize findings = count(),
  by: { compliance.result.object.name, compliance.rule.title }
| sort findings desc
```

### Step 3 — Query Smartscape for Observed Communication Topology

```dql
smartscapeEdges calls
| fieldsAdd
    source_name = getNodeField(source_id, "name"),
    target_name = getNodeField(target_id, "name"),
    src_type = source_type,
    tgt_type = target_type
| filter contains(target_name, "unguard") or contains(source_name, "unguard")
| summarize count(), by:{source_name, target_name, src_type, tgt_type}
| sort count() desc
```

This reveals the exact process display names used in `source_name` — required for building
accurate bridge queries and NetworkPolicy `from:` selectors.

### Step 4 — Query Data Store Edges (before/after comparison signal)

```dql
smartscapeEdges calls, from:-10m
| fieldsAdd
    source_name = getNodeField(source_id, "name"),
    target_name = getNodeField(target_id, "name")
| filter contains(target_name, "mariadb") or contains(target_name, "redis")
| summarize count(), by:{source_name, target_name}
| sort source_name asc
```

Before remediation: returns rows for each process reaching MariaDB or Redis.
After remediation + 10-minute wait: returns 0 rows if NetworkPolicies correctly block access.

### Step 5 — Detect Unauthorized Lateral Movement (before/after signal)

```dql
smartscapeEdges calls, from:-10m
| fieldsAdd
    source_name = getNodeField(source_id, "name"),
    target_name = getNodeField(target_id, "name")
| filter contains(lower(source_name), "php") or contains(lower(source_name), "like")
| filter contains(target_name, "user-auth") or contains(target_name, "unguard")
| fields source_name, target_name
```

This detects like-service (PHP-CLI) making unauthorized HTTP calls to other services.
Before remediation: shows the edge. After: edge absent.

